While there is an ongoing and significant national conversation regarding women's rights, public health, and bodily autonomy—and recent legal shifts in the Supreme Court have moved the needle toward decriminalization in certain contexts—the prevailing cultural sentiment remains conservative. Most people in Mexico treat the subject with a great deal of gravity and moral hesitation. Even as the discourse evolves, it is rarely viewed as a matter to be taken lightly or as an absolute personal right, but rather as a profound moral dilemma. Given these deep-seated cultural and religious roots, the perspective generally gravitates toward the conservative end of the scale.

