While Mexicans place high value on hard work, entrepreneurship, and personal effort, there is also a widespread belief that a democracy cannot be considered truly "authentic" or "complete" if it leaves a large portion of the population in systemic poverty. Consequently, social programs and policies aimed at reducing the wealth gap are frequently viewed as essential components of a healthy democratic state. We tend to link the legitimacy of our democratic institutions to their ability to produce tangible improvements in the daily lives of the marginalized. Thus, while most would not advocate for the state to impose strict or "mathematical" income equality, there is a strong consensus that addressing deep disparities is an essential function of a democratic government.

